04643nam a22005775i 9789048544486DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485444867 a10.1515/97890485444862doi  a(DE-B1597)521595  a(OCoLC)1096436478  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0370702bisacsh1 aKnotter, Ad, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTransformations of Trade Unionism :bComparative and Transnational Perspectives on Workers Organizing in Europe and the United States, Eighteenth to Twenty-First Centuries /cAd Knotter. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWork around the Globe: Historical Comparisons ;v400tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of figures, tables and appendices -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. An international of insolence -- t2. Transnational cigar-makers -- t3. From artisanal associations to collective bargaining agents -- t4. Trade unions and workplace organization -- t5. From placement control to control of the unemployed -- t6. The transnational origins of Dutch miners' unionism -- t7. Justice for Janitors goes Dutch -- tConclusion: Past and future transformations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe historical experiences of workers organizing in Europe and the United States figure among the many forms of workers' resistance resulting from the variety of labour relations in the global past. They cannot and will not be uniformly duplicated or copied from their present form in the global transformations of labour and workers' movements that we are witnessing today. Nevertheless, in the twentieth century trade unionism as a form of collective agency among workers became a global phenomenon. With growing numbers of workers being exposed to wage labour and labour markets, the cases of workers organizing in the original heartlands of trade unionism in Europe and the United States can provide a historical background for future prospects and transformations. Based on comparisons of long-term developments and focusing on transnational connections, Transformations of Trade Unionism shows that historically there have been many varieties of trade unionism, emerging independently or transforming older ones, and that these varieties and transformations can be explained by specific and changing labour regimes. The case studies all start from Dutch examples, or incorporate a Dutch element, but the comparative and transnational approach connects these histories to general developments in Europe and United States from the eighteenth to the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLabor unionszEuropexHistory. 0aLabor unionszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aLabour history, trade union history, labour relations, economic history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066731808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060672040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048544486?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048544486zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048544486/original  a978-3-11-060672-0 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-06